{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504169"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:12:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:12:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2304"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2304"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.15,0.2,0.21,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102036"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2304"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44900"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102036"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents with intermittent wheezing. These symptoms have been present for about two years, but they have worsened over about six months and are most noticeable when he lies flat.\u00a0On further questioning, he has a mild dry cough, but he has had this for several years. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally at weekends. His medications include perindopril and metformin. On examination his blood pressure is 132/84mmHg, pulse 88/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 97% on room air. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic aneurysm","Bronchogenic carcinoma","Thymoma","Retrosternal goitre","Mediastinal lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s chest X-ray shows a large retrosternal mass displacing the trachea laterally and to the right. Whilst there are quite a number of possible causes to consider, the most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrosternal goitre\u003C/strong\u003E. That the mass appears to be extending from or into the neck, is supportive of this diagnosis. Large goitres can compress the trachea and oesophagus, occasionally causing symptoms such as hoarseness of voice, dysphagia and a dry cough. These symptoms are relatively rare and when goitres do produce compressive symptoms, they are most often those that reflect a degree of tracheal compressions - such as wheezing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a round or fusiform dilatation of the aorta on the chest X-ray, which usually occurs in the thoracic aorta. Most of these aneurysm are asymptomatic, but the expanding aneurysm can cause compression of adjacent structures such as the trachea and oesophagus. However, symptoms such as dysphagia and shortness of breath would be very uncommon. Radiologically this mass is seen to extend up into the neck - which would not fit for a thoracic aortic aneurysm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emediastinal lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a similar-looking mass on a chest X-ray, however, it would often be associated with additional symptoms such as night sweats, unexplained weight loss and fever. Mediastinal lymphoma rarely presents with respiratory symptoms such as described by this patient. In addition, the time frame from the onset of his symptoms would make lymphoma an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethymoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a neoplastic mass originating from the thymus gland can present as a mediastinal mass of the chest X-ray. It can present with symptoms of dysphagia and hoarseness of voice but usually, there are other typical symptoms such as shortness of breath, chest pain, superior vena caval obstruction, weakness of facial muscles and muscles of upper extremity which is usually due to myasthenia gravis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBronchogenic carcinoma, particularly small cell carcinoma can often present as a large mediastinal nodal mass but normally not to this degree without symptoms. Chest pain is usually only present if there is chest wall invasion or rib metastases. Some 80% of advanced-stage lung carcinomas present with symptoms due to metastases outside the thorax, particularly bony, intra-cerebral metastasis. Along with that, there would usually be a patient history of chronic smoking or a family history of lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retrosternal goitre are frequently asymptomatic, incidental radiological findings."],"references":["Knobel M. An overview of retrosternal goiter. J Endocrinol Invest. 2021 Apr;44(4):679-691. doi: 10.1007/s40618-020-01391-6. Epub 2020 Aug 11. PMID: 32780357.","Shah PJ, Bright T, Singh SS, Lang CM, Pyragius MD, Malycha P, Edwards JR. Large retrosternal goitre: a diagnostic and management dilemma. Heart Lung Circ. 2006 Apr;15(2):151-2. doi: 10.1016/j.hlc.2005.10.011. Epub 2006 Feb 21. PMID: 16490399."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2304"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19602"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19602"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3a5d8d5c-04a5-495f-9dad-dd67604272ba.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3a5d8d5c-04a5-495f-9dad-dd67604272ba.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":556,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-06T21:11:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T21:12:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2304"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102036"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitab